Introduction¶

This notebook documents the exploration process of Loan Data from Prosper, which is a dataset that contains 113,937 loans with 81 variables on each loan. This data exploration and analysis documentation aims to answer the following major questions:

  1. What factors affect the borrower's rate?
  2. How do the borrower rate affect the other factors?

Preliminary Wrangling¶

This section documents the data wrangling process which involved the gathering, assessment and finally the cleaning of the collected data

Data Assessment¶

The dataset is seen to be relatively large with about 81 variables. The next section of the data wrangling process will begin the data assessment to determine the most important factors to answer the questions posed earlier in the introduction section

In [5]:
# function to return the definition of a given variable
def getDesc(x):
    if x in defin.Variable.values:
        return (defin[defin.Variable == x].iloc[0, 1])
    else: return 'Not a Variable'

To simplify the data assessment process, the first 5 entries across all variables are visually assessed and the description of some of the variables are collected to ascertain the most significant variables to answer the questions presented.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The dataset comprises of 113937 loan data with 81 variables, but for the purpose of this data exploration and analysis, the number of variables have been reduced to 12 variables(Term, LoanStatus, BorrowerRate, ProsperRating (numeric), BorrowerAPR, EmploymentStatus, IsBorrowerHomeowner, EstimatedEffectiveYield, EstimatedLoss, EstimatedReturn, LenderYield, Investors, CreditScoreRangeUpper, LoanOriginalAmount) and also the number of entries have been reduced to 84853 loan entries due to missing information on several variables. The majority of the variables are numerical variables, though there are some boolean, ordered categorical, and string variables.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

The main features of interest in the dataset are the BorrowerRate and the BorrowerAPR would like to find how other variables affect these variables.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

Considering the already cleaned dataset, I expect that the BorrowerRate to be strongly related to the BorrowerAPR. Also, the EstimatedReturn and the EstimatedEffectiveYield are expected to be dependent on the BorrowerRate.

In [51]:
# function to perform square-root transformation
def sqrt_trans(x, inverse=True):
    if not inverse:
         return np.power(x, 0.5)
    else: return np.power(x, 2)
In [52]:
# carry out variable transformations on both the BorrowerRate and the BorrowerAPR

data['BorrowerAPR_trans'] = data.BorrowerAPR.apply(sqrt_trans)

Across the ProsperRating, as the rating scores increase, the values for the investors go up. Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

The Multivariate analysis again confirms the fact that the borrower rate reduces with increasing ProsperRating, and there is also a similar negative relationship between the LoanOriginalAmount and the BorrowerRate.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

There were several interesting interactions between the features. The first is the average borrower rate across each CreditScoreRangeUpper score, the not employed EmploymentStatus appears to have the greatest BorrowerRate average which I find rather surprising. Also, the amount of investors a loan was found to increase with increasing ProsperRating.

Conclusions¶

The analysis focused on some of the features originally present in the dataset and the feature of interest was the BorrowerRate. The main insights gained from the analysis are as follows:

  • There is a strong relationship between the BorrowerRate and the ProsperRating, the BorrowerRate is dependent on the ProsperRating and an approximately negative linear relationship may be seen between these variables
  • The BorrowerRate is dependent on the LoanOriginalAmount and a negative relationship may be observed between them, although it is not as strong as that between the ProsperRating and the BorrowerRate
  • The BorrowerRate and BorrowerAPR are collinear as the have very similar distribution and are highly positively correlated with each other
  • The CreditScoreRangeUpper is negatively related with the average BorrowerRate in a CreditScoreRangeUpper value, and the not employed employment status usually have the highest average BorrowerRate.
  • The EstimatedLoss, EstimatedEffectiveYield and EstimatedReturn are all dependent on the BorrowerRate and they are all positively correlated with the BorrowerRate, although they exhibit non-linear relationships with the BorrowerRate.
